Title: Do sector-specific shocks explain aggregate fluctuations?
Creation-Date: 20050720
Author-Name: Francesco Busato
Author-X-Name-First: Francesco
Author-X-Name-Last: Busato
Author-Name: Alessandro Girardi 
Author-X-Name-First: Alessandro
Author-X-Name-Last: Girardi
Author-Name: Amadeo Argentiero 
Author-X-Name-First: Amadeo
Author-X-Name-Last: Argentiero 
Author-Email: fbusato@econ.au.dk
Author-WorkPlace-Name: Department of Economics, University of Aarhus, Denmark
Author-WorkPlace-Postal: 8000 Aarhus C, Denmark
Author-WorkPlace-Fax: +45 86 13 63 34
Abstract: This paper estimates a reduced form multi-sector real business cycle model that allows for sectorspecific
and cross-sector shocks of two different types: technology shocks and non-technology shocks.
Long run restrictions identify the different kinds of shocks. There are four main findings.
(i) Sector-specific technology shocks explain more than 70 percent of volatilitys productivity on
a sector-by-sector basis; sector-specific non-technology shocks explain, on the other hand, more than
80 percent of employment volatility in each sector. This suggests that technology shocks matters for
explaining within-sector productivity fluctuations.
(ii) Cross-sector technology shocks have very little explanatory power on productivity and
employment, while cross-sector non-technology shocks explain more than 60 percent of employment
that is reallocated across sector; this suggests that the shocks transmission mechanism operates
through non-technology shocks.
(iii) There is no evidence of an aggregate technology shocks for the United States economy;
looking at the aggregate economy might produce misleading results because the relatively larger
sectors drive the dynamic behavior of the aggregate economy. In this respect a disaggregate analysis
may shed light on the mechanisms behind the propagation of shocks across sectors and over time.
(iv) Finally, our analysis suggests that an appropriate real business model for the United States
economy requires at least two sectors, representing, for example, durable and non-durable goods. The
non-durable sector may follow a standard RBC model, while the durable sector should incorporate
consumption habit formation.
Classification-JEL: E2, E3, E32
Keywords: Long-run Restrictions, Sector-Specific Shocks, Real Business Cycle
Length: 36
