Abstract: For a small open economy where the government is restricted to raise revenue using
border taxes only, the optimal structure of border taxes is considered. As a matter 
of normalization exports and the supply to the market of the primary factor may be 
assumed to be untaxed, but that the household use of the primary factor and domestic 
consumption of the export good cannot be taxed is nevertheless a constraint; this 
insight provides the key to understanding what determines the optimal tariff structure. 
The optimal border tax structure is derived for both exogenous and endogenous labour 
supply, and the results are interpreted in the spirit of the Corlett-Hague results 
for the optimal tax structure in a closed economy and compared with results from CGE 
models.
